I did work on finite automata theory, which

532
00:32:24,460 --> 00:32:29,660
had certain relationships to early programming languages.

533
00:32:29,660 --> 00:32:33,020
And there were neutral investigations,

534
00:32:33,020 --> 00:32:36,580
cooperative investigations, looking at these contexts.

535
00:32:36,580 --> 00:32:42,860
But it's basically forms of formal languages,

536
00:32:42,860 --> 00:32:47,220
properties somewhat similar to natural languages.

537
00:32:47,220 --> 00:32:52,500
I worked on them in the early 50s around the period

538
00:32:52,500 --> 00:32:55,500
that programming languages were being developed,

539
00:32:55,500 --> 00:32:59,380
and the two interact in a number of ways.

540
00:32:59,380 --> 00:33:03,380
So if you look at a textbook on programming,

541
00:33:03,380 --> 00:33:06,940
you'll find things about, sometimes called

542
00:33:06,940 --> 00:33:10,940
the Chomsky hierarchy, the hierarchy of possible formal

543
00:33:10,940 --> 00:33:16,900
languages, which have various analogs in programming theory.

544
00:33:16,900 --> 00:33:20,540
They capture some features of natural language,

545
00:33:20,540 --> 00:33:26,580
but they also correspond to certain types of automata,

546
00:33:26,580 --> 00:33:30,420
linear bounded automata, push down storage automata,

547
00:33:30,420 --> 00:33:35,260
standard interrelate with formal systems that

548
00:33:35,260 --> 00:33:38,100
capture some of the properties of language, which

549
00:33:38,100 --> 00:33:40,020
is a topic of some interest.

550
00:33:40,020 --> 00:33:45,460
But it didn't enable programming.

551
00:33:45,460 --> 00:33:50,380
I want to mention some theories of incognitive science

552
00:33:50,380 --> 00:33:53,500
and philosophy that you have attacked.

553
00:33:53,500 --> 00:33:56,620
I don't know of a softer word to accurately describe it,

554
00:33:56,620 --> 00:33:58,980
and want to just get your reflections on it.

555
00:33:58,980 --> 00:34:03,020
After many decades of looking back,

556
00:34:03,020 --> 00:34:05,820
first is behaviorism.

557
00:34:05,820 --> 00:34:10,580
What was it about behaviorism that you found erroneous,

558
00:34:10,580 --> 00:34:15,460
and how do you reflect now looking back over the decades?

559
00:34:15,460 --> 00:34:19,500
In my view, behaviorism was a radical departure

560
00:34:19,500 --> 00:34:20,900
from the sciences.

561
00:34:20,900 --> 00:34:23,260
First of all, behaviorism varied.

562
00:34:23,260 --> 00:34:27,180
But the form of behaviorism that was pretty much

563
00:34:27,180 --> 00:34:30,620
dominant in the period of creation

564
00:34:30,620 --> 00:34:33,900
of modern cognitive science was largely

565
00:34:33,900 --> 00:34:36,220
skinnerian behaviorism.

566
00:34:36,220 --> 00:34:40,100
It was picked up by Van Quine, one

567
00:34:40,100 --> 00:34:43,260
of the most influential philosophers of language.

568
00:34:44,020 --> 00:34:49,620
Work like Word and Object based very explicitly

569
00:34:49,620 --> 00:34:53,620
on operant conditioning, skinnerian behaviorism.

570
00:34:53,620 --> 00:34:57,220
And that was all the rage in Cambridge in the 1950s.

571
00:34:57,220 --> 00:34:59,860
It was virtual dogma.

572
00:34:59,860 --> 00:35:02,100
Skinners, William James Lectures,

573
00:35:02,100 --> 00:35:04,540
came out in the late 40s.

574
00:35:04,540 --> 00:35:06,460
The book itself, Herbal Behavior,

575
00:35:06,460 --> 00:35:08,340
came out about a decade later.

576
00:35:08,340 --> 00:35:11,340
But it was whatever it was doing.

577
00:35:11,380 --> 00:35:15,020
Well, there were various chips in the armor

578
00:35:15,020 --> 00:35:16,620
that began to develop.

579
00:35:16,620 --> 00:35:19,980
Some of them were within psychology itself.

580
00:35:19,980 --> 00:35:22,540
So George Miller, one of the founders

581
00:35:22,540 --> 00:35:26,260
of cognitive psychology, a close friend,

582
00:35:26,260 --> 00:35:28,060
worked closely with him for many years.

583
00:35:28,060 --> 00:35:29,980
We published together.

584
00:35:29,980 --> 00:35:35,460
Even before this started, he did some crucial experiments

585
00:35:35,460 --> 00:35:38,100
which raised serious questions.

586
00:35:38,140 --> 00:35:39,900
So for example, take the sentence,

587
00:35:39,900 --> 00:35:45,300
and John went to the store from any sentence.

588
00:35:45,300 --> 00:35:48,180
The standard theory of perception of speech

589
00:35:48,180 --> 00:35:53,260
was you have a certain guess about the first word,

590
00:35:53,260 --> 00:35:55,660
then you have a guess about the second word,

591
00:35:55,660 --> 00:35:58,460
the probability that you're right both times decreases,

592
00:35:58,460 --> 00:36:00,300
of course.

593
00:36:00,300 --> 00:36:02,660
By the time you get to the last word,

594
00:36:02,660 --> 00:36:05,980
it should be very hard to understand in a long sentence.

595
00:36:05,980 --> 00:36:08,820
Well, George showed that it's the opposite.

596
00:36:08,820 --> 00:36:11,060
You don't understand the early words

597
00:36:11,060 --> 00:36:13,620
until you get to the last word, which

598
00:36:13,620 --> 00:36:16,900
means that you're forming the thought in your mind.

599
00:36:16,900 --> 00:36:18,820
And the thought in your mind is telling you

600
00:36:18,820 --> 00:36:21,180
what those early noises were.

601
00:36:21,180 --> 00:36:23,700
By now, there's lots of work on this.

602
00:36:23,700 --> 00:36:27,180
Well, that just didn't fit at all with behaviorism.

603
00:36:27,180 --> 00:36:30,740
There was very important work in neuroscience

604
00:36:30,740 --> 00:36:36,660
by Carl Lashley, his work on serial behavior around 1950.

605
00:36:36,660 --> 00:36:39,500
It just totally undercut behaviorism,

606
00:36:39,500 --> 00:36:42,820
showed that there are overall patterns in behavior

607
00:36:42,820 --> 00:36:44,580
that simply just don't work anything

608
00:36:44,580 --> 00:36:47,180
like the waivers' models.

609
00:36:47,180 --> 00:36:50,020
Nobody looked at that.

610
00:36:50,020 --> 00:36:54,540
I found it in the early 50s because it was brought to my

611
00:36:54,540 --> 00:36:59,260
attention by an art historian, Harsh Piro,

612
00:37:00,060 --> 00:37:02,020
you might be interested in this.

613
00:37:02,020 --> 00:37:05,620
Looked at it, so totally wiped out behaviorism.

614
00:37:05,620 --> 00:37:10,260
There was other work going on in European, what's

615
00:37:10,260 --> 00:37:14,500
called ethology, comparative biology,

616
00:37:14,500 --> 00:37:18,860
the Lawrence, Timberg, and others,

617
00:37:18,860 --> 00:37:23,700
which was foreign to the environment in which cognitive

618
00:37:23,700 --> 00:37:26,180
science grew up.

619
00:37:26,180 --> 00:37:29,460
But the main thing was the work on language

620
00:37:29,460 --> 00:37:33,740
that I and others started doing in the early 50s

621
00:37:33,740 --> 00:37:39,100
was completely inconsistent with all behaviorist assumptions.

622
00:37:39,100 --> 00:37:43,860
And there was just no connection between them.

623
00:37:43,860 --> 00:37:45,780
You couldn't relate them.

624
00:37:45,780 --> 00:37:51,180
And then when Skinner's book appeared,

625
00:37:51,180 --> 00:37:53,220
you could read through it, and you

626
00:37:53,220 --> 00:37:56,980
could see that it's all hand-waving.

627
00:37:56,980 --> 00:37:59,060
There's nothing there.

628
00:37:59,060 --> 00:38:01,460
Incidentally, around that time, even

629
00:38:01,460 --> 00:38:05,380
within the behaviorist framework,

630
00:38:05,380 --> 00:38:07,820
there were cracks developing.

631
00:38:07,820 --> 00:38:11,100
So there was work by some of Skinner's students,

632
00:38:11,100 --> 00:38:13,660
incidentally important work, which

633
00:38:13,660 --> 00:38:16,420
showed that animals just didn't behave

634
00:38:16,420 --> 00:38:18,980
by these pattern paradigms.

635
00:38:18,980 --> 00:38:20,900
That they seemed to be working only

636
00:38:20,900 --> 00:38:25,940
if you picked experimental conditions that essentially

637
00:38:25,940 --> 00:38:28,980
adapted instinctive behavior.

638
00:38:28,980 --> 00:38:33,140
So you can teach a pigeon to play ping-pong

639
00:38:33,140 --> 00:38:36,420
because pigeons peck.

640
00:38:36,420 --> 00:38:39,140
So you can modify the pecking behavior.

641
00:38:39,140 --> 00:38:42,780
But basically, it was all falling apart from many points

642
00:38:42,780 --> 00:38:43,980
of view.

643
00:38:43,980 --> 00:38:48,220
And my own view, as it was a bad mistake from the first place,

644
00:38:48,220 --> 00:38:51,860
you don't study any subject by saying,

645
00:38:51,860 --> 00:38:55,180
let's keep to the superficial manifestations

646
00:38:55,180 --> 00:38:58,060
and not look at what's going on internally.

647
00:38:58,060 --> 00:38:59,420
You want to understand it?

648
00:38:59,420 --> 00:39:02,140
You're going to have to look at what's going on internally.

649
00:39:02,140 --> 00:39:03,740
You don't see it.

650
00:39:03,740 --> 00:39:06,260
You can't do experiments right on it.

651
00:39:06,260 --> 00:39:09,220
You have to study it in indirect ways,

652
00:39:09,220 --> 00:39:11,980
the way physics, chemistry, biology,

653
00:39:11,980 --> 00:39:13,980
every other subject developed.

654
00:39:13,980 --> 00:39:18,260
Linguistic relativity, the so-called Worf hypothesis,

655
00:39:18,260 --> 00:39:21,900
where language determines thought in the strong version

656
00:39:21,900 --> 00:39:24,620
or at least influences thought in the weak version,

657
00:39:24,620 --> 00:39:27,540
that the structure of a language affects the speaker's

658
00:39:27,540 --> 00:39:29,340
worldview or cognition.

659
00:39:29,340 --> 00:39:32,660
And therefore, when people have different languages,

660
00:39:32,660 --> 00:39:37,380
their perceptions are related to the languages they speak,

661
00:39:37,380 --> 00:39:43,220
as opposed to a broad human capability.

662
00:39:43,300 --> 00:39:47,860
That hypothesis, the superior Worf hypothesis,

663
00:39:47,860 --> 00:39:52,500
has been around for 80 or so years.

664
00:39:52,500 --> 00:39:55,220
Investigation of its series of investigation

665
00:39:55,220 --> 00:39:57,540
began in the early 50s.

666
00:39:57,540 --> 00:40:02,180
First person to study it was Eric Leneberg.

667
00:40:02,180 --> 00:40:05,020
We were grad students together, personal friend.

668
00:40:05,020 --> 00:40:07,860
He went on to found biology of language.

669
00:40:07,860 --> 00:40:10,220
But his first work was actually as a student

670
00:40:10,220 --> 00:40:15,500
on the Worf hypothesis, experimental work.

671
00:40:15,500 --> 00:40:16,780
Couldn't find anything.

672
00:40:16,780 --> 00:40:19,740
Everything you tried, you got some superficial results,

673
00:40:19,740 --> 00:40:20,980
but nothing.

674
00:40:20,980 --> 00:40:24,260
Well, it's now 75 years later.

675
00:40:24,260 --> 00:40:26,700
There isn't a lot more to say.

676
00:40:26,700 --> 00:40:30,140
There's some evidence.

677
00:40:30,140 --> 00:40:34,500
Some of the Lila Gleitman, who I mentioned before,

678
00:40:34,500 --> 00:40:39,020
carefully analyzed and did experimental work

679
00:40:39,020 --> 00:40:43,540
on some of the alleged evidence that fell apart.

680
00:40:43,540 --> 00:40:47,180
There's a few things around that seem possible,

681
00:40:47,180 --> 00:40:51,540
but pickings are very slim.

682
00:40:51,540 --> 00:40:54,220
I mean, there's some respects in which it's obviously true.

683
00:40:54,220 --> 00:41:00,340
So as Leneberg pointed out, 75 you found, 75 years ago,

684
00:41:00,340 --> 00:41:08,420
if you study a language that we have a distinction between red

685
00:41:08,420 --> 00:41:12,180
and orange and pink, say, but their languages don't.

686
00:41:12,180 --> 00:41:14,220
They haven't been studying Hopi.

687
00:41:14,220 --> 00:41:17,100
Just use the same word for that spectrum.

688
00:41:17,100 --> 00:41:20,220
So he found perfectly predictably

689
00:41:20,220 --> 00:41:24,820
that if you use, say, memory texts, tests,

690
00:41:24,820 --> 00:41:25,820
did you ever see that?

691
00:41:25,820 --> 00:41:30,540
Did you see this shade of color a minute ago?

692
00:41:30,540 --> 00:41:34,100
You'll do better if you have names.

693
00:41:34,100 --> 00:41:37,260
So in a way, the language affects perception,

694
00:41:37,260 --> 00:41:41,380
but in such a trivial way that it's of no interest.

695
00:41:41,380 --> 00:41:43,900
And there isn't much more than that.

696
00:41:43,900 --> 00:41:49,380
Logical positivism, which was the rage in the early 20th century

697
00:41:49,380 --> 00:41:52,780
that said that really there are only two kinds of truths

698
00:41:52,780 --> 00:41:57,900
and even only two kinds of intellectual activities

699
00:41:57,900 --> 00:42:00,580
worth pursuing, those that are empirical

700
00:42:00,580 --> 00:42:02,860
with a scientific method and those that are purely

701
00:42:02,860 --> 00:42:04,660
logical with a deduction.

702
00:42:04,700 --> 00:42:08,620
Everything else is basically non-stets.

703
00:42:08,620 --> 00:42:11,740
Well, logical positivism was an important movement

704
00:42:11,740 --> 00:42:16,620
in the 20s, early 30s.

705
00:42:16,620 --> 00:42:21,940
By the late 30s, its major figures

706
00:42:21,940 --> 00:42:25,100
were drifting away from it.

707
00:42:25,100 --> 00:42:32,420
Karnap, Temple, others, Quine, just moving away from it.

708
00:42:32,460 --> 00:42:37,900
And it became influential in linguistics and psychology

709
00:42:37,900 --> 00:42:43,220
after it was declining philosophy and declining

710
00:42:43,220 --> 00:42:44,140
for good reasons.

711
00:42:44,140 --> 00:42:46,580
There were internal critiques.

712
00:42:46,580 --> 00:42:49,820
But it did have a big influence on linguistics

713
00:42:49,820 --> 00:42:56,100
through Leonard Bloomfield, who saw himself as a strict.

714
00:42:56,100 --> 00:42:59,340
He was the major linguist in the early 20th century.

715
00:42:59,340 --> 00:43:02,420
He did very good work in many areas.

716
00:43:02,420 --> 00:43:05,940
But in this area, he was very much misled

717
00:43:05,940 --> 00:43:10,940
by picking up an early form of logical positivism, which

718
00:43:10,940 --> 00:43:12,660
was not viable.

719
00:43:12,660 --> 00:43:17,220
But so I think it's an important, made important contributions,

720
00:43:17,220 --> 00:43:22,100
important residue, developed sense in other directions.

721
00:43:22,100 --> 00:43:27,980
So if you look at Quine, Copper, Karnap, major figures,

722
00:43:28,580 --> 00:43:32,940
Wittgenstein was totally rejected.

723
00:43:32,940 --> 00:43:39,700
Then it just is no longer a coherent viable movement.

724
00:43:39,700 --> 00:43:42,660
What is your view of contemporary field

725
00:43:42,660 --> 00:43:47,380
or subfield of philosophy of language, which subsumes

726
00:43:47,380 --> 00:43:50,180
a great deal of what we're talking about and even more

727
00:43:50,180 --> 00:43:50,820
than that?

728
00:43:50,820 --> 00:43:51,980
What are the categories?

729
00:43:51,980 --> 00:43:53,540
What are your reflections on it?

730
00:43:53,540 --> 00:43:57,140
Well, I've been a pretty short critic of it.

731
00:43:57,140 --> 00:43:58,820
I've been book after book.

732
00:43:58,820 --> 00:44:00,940
I don't want to go through that.

733
00:44:00,940 --> 00:44:03,460
I mean, there is important work.

734
00:44:03,460 --> 00:44:07,460
But a lot of it, I think, is seriously misguided.

735
00:44:07,460 --> 00:44:11,180
I could go into details if written about it.

736
00:44:11,180 --> 00:44:13,220
So for example, take, say, Quine,

737
00:44:13,220 --> 00:44:16,140
who was the Quine and Wittgenstein

738
00:44:16,140 --> 00:44:21,100
to the leading figures of modern philosophy of language.

739
00:44:21,100 --> 00:44:24,900
Both of them accepted for Quine, who

740
00:44:24,900 --> 00:44:26,900
was a strict Schenarian.

741
00:44:26,900 --> 00:44:32,180
Language, in his words, is a complex of dispositions

742
00:44:32,180 --> 00:44:36,900
to respond to present stimuli.

743
00:44:36,900 --> 00:44:39,060
There's nothing to do with language.

744
00:44:39,060 --> 00:44:41,620
I mean, it didn't develop that way.

745
00:44:41,620 --> 00:44:43,740
It's not used that way.

746
00:44:43,740 --> 00:44:45,580
Wittgenstein, the late Wittgenstein,

747
00:44:45,580 --> 00:44:48,980
who was interested in language, it was kind of aphoristic.

748
00:44:48,980 --> 00:44:53,620
You know, try to give an organized system.

749
00:44:53,620 --> 00:44:58,020
But if you look at his comments on acquisition of language,

750
00:44:58,020 --> 00:45:01,540
they're strict behaviorist.

751
00:45:01,540 --> 00:45:05,140
You know, his language games, somebody

752
00:45:05,140 --> 00:45:10,780
is showing a rock and somebody says rock and imitated.

753
00:45:10,780 --> 00:45:12,780
That's how you learned rock.

754
00:45:12,780 --> 00:45:14,780
Nothing like that happens.

755
00:45:14,780 --> 00:45:17,820
I mean, there's tons of experimental evidence by now,

756
00:45:17,820 --> 00:45:20,580
even just observational evidence.

757
00:45:20,580 --> 00:45:25,940
And I think while there are doubtless major contributions,

758
00:45:25,940 --> 00:45:27,780
some of them, a lot of the work, I think,

759
00:45:27,780 --> 00:45:29,780
is off on the wrong track.

760
00:45:29,780 --> 00:45:34,020
So the main contributions, I think, have been in semantics.

761
00:45:34,020 --> 00:45:37,580
Donald Davidson's work on event semantics

762
00:45:37,580 --> 00:45:40,500
has turned out to be very productive and influential.

763
00:45:40,500 --> 00:45:46,220
It was picked up by Languist philosophers, James Higginbotham,

764
00:45:46,220 --> 00:45:50,660
Paul Trotsky, others, and it's turned into, my view,

765
00:45:50,660 --> 00:45:52,980
one of the most promising approaches

766
00:45:52,980 --> 00:45:55,940
to the general semantics of language.

767
00:45:55,940 --> 00:45:57,300
It's called philosophy.

768
00:45:57,300 --> 00:45:59,740
I don't know why it's called philosophy.

769
00:45:59,740 --> 00:46:03,060
It's basically a good, serious study

770
00:46:03,060 --> 00:46:05,580
of the semantics of natural language.

771
00:46:05,580 --> 00:46:08,660
Analytics philosophy versus continental philosophy.

772
00:46:08,660 --> 00:46:11,180
You're classified as an analytic philosopher.

773
00:46:11,180 --> 00:46:14,580
You've had some engagements with continental philosophers

774
00:46:14,580 --> 00:46:15,580
famously.

775
00:46:15,580 --> 00:46:19,540
What is your reflection on the dichotomy

776
00:46:19,540 --> 00:46:21,460
between them, the artificial?

777
00:46:24,820 --> 00:46:27,340
How do you see going forward?

778
00:46:27,340 --> 00:46:29,420
Well, actually, a good deal of my work

779
00:46:29,420 --> 00:46:35,020
is on continental philosophy from the 17th through the 19th

780
00:46:35,020 --> 00:46:49,500
century, Descartes, Hume, Locke, onto the philosophers

781
00:46:49,500 --> 00:46:53,980
of Humboldt on through the 19th century.

782
00:46:53,980 --> 00:46:59,500
Contemporary continental philosophy is quite different.

783
00:46:59,500 --> 00:47:03,420
There's work that I find interesting,

784
00:47:03,420 --> 00:47:06,220
close to a number of others.

785
00:47:06,220 --> 00:47:11,780
But most of the modern work, either I don't understand it

786
00:47:11,780 --> 00:47:15,700
or I don't find it very interesting.

787
00:47:15,700 --> 00:47:19,180
My own background is in what's called analytic philosophy,

788
00:47:19,180 --> 00:47:21,900
though I was, as I've just mentioned,

789
00:47:21,900 --> 00:47:25,740
I've been rather critical of a lot of the ways it's developed.

790
00:47:25,740 --> 00:47:31,540
But I think basically on the way to finding

791
00:47:31,540 --> 00:47:35,420
serious understanding of the way the mind works,

792
00:47:35,420 --> 00:47:36,980
the way the world works.

793
